UNIVERSITY OF NOTRE DAME MEDIA CONFERENCE
September 25, 2005
Charlie Weis
START_OF_INTERVIEW_TEXT







<p>	Q.  Are you glad to get that over with?</p>
<p>	Q.  Can you talk about the big plays?  You mentioned a lot of the big plays.  When you look back at the film, are these things that are fixable, are you getting out-athleted? </p>
<p>	Q.  How important is it to have the lead at halftime?  You're outscoring opponents 54 to 19 in the second quarter.  Does that affect the confidence of your opponents?</p>
<p>	Q.  With you liking the offensive side the ball so much --</p>
<p>	Q.  With the offense having the ball for 37 minutes yesterday, can they be on the field too much? </p>
<p>	Q.  Can you talk about Jeff Samardzija's body control, what it means?</p>
<p>	Q.  Would you call it exceptional compared to other guys his size?</p>
<p>	Q.  The zone blitz, we've seen a lot more of it the last few years.  Can you talk about, from a quarterback standpoint, the ability to recognize it, that process? </p>
<p>	Q.  Can you talk about your meeting last week with Montana Mazurkiewicz. </p>
<p>	Q.  I saw that Terrail Lambert got in the game.  Can you evaluate him, maybe some of the other reserves that got to play yesterday? </p>
<p>	Q.  After four games, what about this team maybe has surprised you and what maybe are the points of emphasis for improvement that you can share without giving away anything? </p>
<p>	Q.  As you head into this Purdue game, this is going to be the last game before a bye week.  Do you handle players that may be a little bit banged up a little differently?  Do you maybe slow them down a little bit so they can have the benefit of a couple weeks of rest?</p>
<p>	Q.  Speaking of bumps and bruises, have you learned of anything more on Bob that you're able to share?</p>
<p>	Q.  How old are your kids?</p>
<p>	Q.  (No microphone.)</p>
<p>	Q.  (No microphone.)</p>
<p>	Q.  (No microphone.)</p>


